The paper deals with privacy-preserving computations, which is a topic that falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). The use of Renyi divergence and the focus on quantitative results suggest that the paper may also be relevant to information theory (cs.IT). The unification of concentrated differential privacy with approximate differential privacy involves machine learning techniques, which could place the paper in the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves the analysis of algorithms, which could place it in the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) or computational complexity (cs.CC).
